18:23.601 --> 18:25.669
I'll bear that in mind.

18:25.671 --> 18:27.204
It's not natural for a man...

18:27.206 --> 18:28.138
Nature's the goal?

18:28.140 --> 18:31.274
Most mammals mate for life.
For life! That's nature.

18:31.276 --> 18:32.742
Some species, the surviving mate

18:32.744 --> 18:34.811
remains faithful and monogamous

18:34.813 --> 18:36.780
even after the mate has died.

18:36.782 --> 18:38.582
Let me renew
your subscription to Nova.

18:38.584 --> 18:41.751
I don't have to stand for this.
I can outrun you.

18:41.753 --> 18:43.320
Oh, yeah?

18:46.557 --> 18:48.492
[GULLS CAWING]

18:52.497 --> 18:55.332
RACHEL:
He goes out there every night.

18:55.466 --> 18:57.334
Thursday, he was out all night.

18:57.336 --> 18:59.402
ESTHER:
Doing what?

19:01.639 --> 19:04.541
Staring at the ocean, I guess.

19:06.544 --> 19:07.777
Is it, like, a sickness?

19:07.779 --> 19:11.314
In your psychology classes,
do they have a name for this?

19:11.316 --> 19:15.385
Oh, yes. It's...
he's nuts.

19:15.387 --> 19:18.255
[BOTH LAUGH]

19:20.791 --> 19:24.528
He will be all right.
It's just...

19:26.597 --> 19:28.632
He really loved her.

19:34.305 --> 19:36.439
He's not the only one.

19:37.742 --> 19:39.543
I know.

19:51.189 --> 19:52.422
Hey.

19:52.424 --> 19:53.456
Hey.

19:53.458 --> 19:56.927
You're probably beginning to
notice, I never leave.

19:56.929 --> 19:57.929
Why is that?

19:57.930 --> 20:00.330
I live next door.
My parents are away.

20:00.332 --> 20:03.333
I'm orphaned here
for the weekend.

20:04.669 --> 20:06.203
You know about this weekend?

20:06.205 --> 20:10.373
Oh, yes. It's, um...
an anniversary.

20:10.375 --> 20:14.211
Not just that.
It's the anniversary.

20:14.213 --> 20:16.947
Dress-up dinner,
castle-building, karaoke.

20:16.949 --> 20:18.215
Gillian started it.

20:18.217 --> 20:22.786
They choose stupid songs you'd
never admit to liking.

20:22.788 --> 20:23.553
They what?

20:23.555 --> 20:24.621
A lot of Barry Manilow.

20:24.623 --> 20:28.625
Weekend tradition.
This is the Gillian weekend.

20:30.962 --> 20:34.631
<b>♪ ["YOU MAKE ME FEEL LIKE DANCING" ♪
♪ BY LEO SAYER PLAYS] ♪</b>

20:35.533 --> 20:38.835
♪ Oh ♪ [CLEARS THROAT]

20:38.837 --> 20:41.471
♪ Ah ah ♪

20:41.473 --> 20:43.740
♪ Oh ♪

20:43.742 --> 20:45.976
♪ Ah ah ♪

20:45.978 --> 20:50.647
<i>♪ You've got</i>
<i>a cute way of talkin' ♪</i>

20:51.415 --> 20:55.418
<i>♪ You got the better of me ♪</i>

20:55.953 --> 20:59.990
<i>♪ Just snap your fingers</i>
<i>and I'm walkin' ♪</i>

20:59.992 --> 21:02.626
<i>♪ Like a dog hangin'</i>
<i>on a leash ♪</i>

21:02.628 --> 21:04.027
What, are you kidding?

21:04.029 --> 21:05.495
This is your song?

21:05.497 --> 21:05.996
Yeah, so?

21:05.998 --> 21:08.965
You're supposed to choose
songs you're ashamed of.

21:08.967 --> 21:10.900
This is a classic!
I love this song!

21:10.902 --> 21:14.004
♪ You make me feel
like dancin' ♪

21:14.006 --> 21:16.306
BOTH:
♪ I want to dance
the night away ♪

21:16.308 --> 21:19.342
♪ You make me feel like dancin ♪

21:19.344 --> 21:20.810
♪ I want to dance
the night away ♪

21:20.812 --> 21:24.948
♪ You make me feel
like dancin' ♪

21:24.950 --> 21:26.283
[LAUGHTER]

21:26.285 --> 21:27.751
Come on, let's go again.

21:27.753 --> 21:30.053
No, I don't really wanna.

21:30.688 --> 21:32.656
Oh, you look fabulous.

21:32.658 --> 21:33.823
I know.

21:33.825 --> 21:35.959
Might want to lose the gum.

21:38.362 --> 21:40.630
Or not.

21:41.465 --> 21:43.066
He's not gonna fall for you.

21:43.068 --> 21:47.037
Live people can't
compete with dead ones.

21:47.039 --> 21:49.372
Ask anybody.

21:49.374 --> 21:50.874
Thank you.

21:58.549 --> 22:00.817
DAVID:
I don't think so!

22:01.085 --> 22:03.420
[SONG CONTINUES IN BACKGROUND]

22:03.422 --> 22:06.022
<i>♪ You make me feel</i>
<i>like dancin' ♪</i>

22:06.024 --> 22:08.425
<i>♪ I feel like dancin' ♪</i>
DAVID AND PAUL: Whoo.

22:08.427 --> 22:10.393
<i>♪ Dancin' ♪</i>
DAVID AND PAUL: Whoo.

22:10.395 --> 22:11.428
<i>♪ Dance the night away ♪</i>

22:11.430 --> 22:13.763
<i>♪ I feel like dancin' ♪</i>
DAVID AND PAUL: Whoo.

22:13.765 --> 22:16.366
<i>♪ Dancin' ♪</i>
BOTH: Ahh.

22:18.769 --> 22:20.537
[MUSIC STOPS]

22:20.539 --> 22:25.375
I'm sorry, we were, uh, we were
just practicing for karaoke.

22:25.377 --> 22:29.646
Sorry. I heard the sound,
couldn't quite believe it.

22:29.648 --> 22:30.680
We're sorry.

22:30.682 --> 22:32.849
Me too. You know what?

22:33.617 --> 22:35.385
I miss Esther.

22:35.720 --> 22:37.587
PAUL:
Sugarplum?

22:37.755 --> 22:40.757
I think there's a plan
to give us private time.

22:40.759 --> 22:44.461
The plan is to
get me over Gillian.

22:44.729 --> 22:48.765
It's been two years.
I'm not over her.

22:50.101 --> 22:52.001
I see.

22:52.003 --> 22:56.005
You can relax, 'cause if it
makes you feel any better,

22:56.007 --> 22:58.041
you're not my type.

22:58.743 --> 23:00.110
Thank you.

23:01.545 --> 23:04.948
Well... we'll see
you at dinner.

23:04.950 --> 23:06.649
Dinner, yes.

23:11.789 --> 23:13.957
First off...
Not too much.

23:13.959 --> 23:19.462
I would like to toast us all
for looking so fantastic.

23:19.464 --> 23:20.163
Absolutely.

23:20.165 --> 23:20.930
Especially me.

23:20.932 --> 23:23.767
It took me an hour to
get into this dress.

23:23.769 --> 23:25.535
And ten seconds
for me to imagine

23:25.537 --> 23:27.704
you out of it,
Miss Teen Succulent.

23:27.706 --> 23:29.005
All right, glasses up.

23:29.007 --> 23:30.473
Sorry.

23:30.475 --> 23:31.708
To all of us.

23:31.710 --> 23:32.876
Cheers.

23:32.878 --> 23:36.446
Ching ching.
Okay, I'm hungry. Let's eat.

23:36.614 --> 23:39.048
Rachel said you have a baby.

23:40.518 --> 23:41.518
You have a baby?

23:41.520 --> 23:44.421
Yes, I have a little boy.
He's 3 years old.

23:44.423 --> 23:46.156
And why I'm not
back home with him

23:46.158 --> 23:47.724
right now completely escapes me.

23:47.726 --> 23:50.794
If you don't mind my being
a nosy little bug,

23:50.796 --> 23:52.429
what happened to the father?

23:52.431 --> 23:54.164
I mean, I know you're divorced.

23:54.166 --> 23:56.733
He cheated on her, bad.

23:59.036 --> 24:00.837
Rachel said.

24:06.177 --> 24:09.112
Yes, my husband is
out of the picture.

24:09.114 --> 24:11.581
I have complete custody.

24:12.616 --> 24:14.684
Completely out of
the picture, David.

24:14.686 --> 24:18.822
ESTHER:
Did you hear that?
That's good news.

24:18.824 --> 24:23.626
So, how come you don't have
children? Do you shoot blanks?

24:23.628 --> 24:25.829
That's a personal
question, Cindy.

24:25.831 --> 24:29.165
I mean, if you really
want to know...

24:30.501 --> 24:31.901
Can I tell her?

24:32.203 --> 24:34.471
You might as well.

24:35.039 --> 24:38.541
We were afraid that
they'd turn out like you.

24:38.543 --> 24:42.212
[LAUGHTER]

24:42.214 --> 24:43.880
You are such a child.

24:43.882 --> 24:45.782
Who's helping me
with the castle tomorrow?

24:45.784 --> 24:48.885
We've got to be on the beach
by 7 a.m. Judging's at 2.00.

24:48.887 --> 24:52.489
ESTHER:
7 a.m.? I thought we were going
to the cemetery tomorrow.

24:52.491 --> 24:54.524
No time.
We've got to start early.

24:54.526 --> 24:58.228
I want to beat Megan Weeks. I've
lost to her three years running.

24:58.230 --> 24:59.963
She's ungracious, arrogant,

24:59.965 --> 25:01.165
and this year, she's gonna gag

25:01.166 --> 25:03.800
on the taste of
unmitigated defeat.

25:03.802 --> 25:06.069
She's 9.

25:07.137 --> 25:09.706
This is my entry tomorrow.

25:09.708 --> 25:11.508
As you can see,
I'm gonna need some help.

25:11.510 --> 25:15.512
Here's an aerial view.
Could you get the end of this?

25:15.514 --> 25:17.013
[WHISTLES]

25:17.015 --> 25:20.884
[SCOFFS]

25:23.621 --> 25:25.755
What?

25:25.757 --> 25:27.023
You have blueprints?

25:27.025 --> 25:28.291
Sure. This takes organization.

25:28.293 --> 25:32.295
Look at these columns.
They're Corinthian.

25:32.297 --> 25:34.597
How long did it
take you to do that?

25:34.599 --> 25:36.165
PAUL:
Esther.

25:36.734 --> 25:38.835
I don't know. Does it matter?

25:38.837 --> 25:40.103
Does it matter?

25:40.105 --> 25:41.004
Pumpkin.

25:41.006 --> 25:42.238
You're a professor of
literature.

25:42.240 --> 25:45.642
You spend your time
meeting with sand engineers?

25:45.644 --> 25:47.944
We build castles every year.

25:47.946 --> 25:48.811
Not with forklifts.

25:48.813 --> 25:52.248
You'll need permits
for that kind of construction.

25:52.250 --> 25:54.651
What's the problem, Esther?

25:55.286 --> 25:57.153
PAUL:
Honeybuns.

25:58.055 --> 25:59.289
PAUL:
Sweetcakes.

25:59.291 --> 26:01.691
I'd like to know the problem.

26:04.728 --> 26:06.095
No problem.

26:12.736 --> 26:13.970
I want to know the problem.

26:13.972 --> 26:15.705
You want to know the problem?

26:15.707 --> 26:19.275
Let me see if I can
locate the problem for you.

26:19.277 --> 26:20.877
You're living on an island,

26:20.879 --> 26:23.246
a practically
deserted island in winter.

26:23.248 --> 26:24.614
You're doing nothing.

26:24.616 --> 26:25.348
I'm writing a book.

26:25.350 --> 26:26.816
What have you written?
Let me see.

26:26.818 --> 26:28.084
I'm the only one
who gets to read it.

26:28.086 --> 26:30.954
Everyone else has to wait
until it's finished.

26:30.956 --> 26:31.921
You're protecting him.

26:31.923 --> 26:35.892
I'm not protecting him.
Don't be reading my mind!

26:35.894 --> 26:37.927
Can't we once eat without having

26:37.929 --> 26:39.696
a free-for-all?
I can't stand it!

26:39.698 --> 26:41.931
Butt your nose right in.
Stick it in snug.

26:41.933 --> 26:44.901
Can we just regroup?
We've got a terrific soup here.

26:44.903 --> 26:48.037
Come on in! Wreck my life!
It's only mine!

26:48.039 --> 26:49.806
It's been two years!

26:49.808 --> 26:51.941
Two years!
Hey!

26:53.177 --> 26:55.845
Listen to yourselves.

26:56.280 --> 27:00.249
Can't we once not
do this, one time?

27:07.324 --> 27:10.393
Maybe you're not happy.
I don't know.

27:10.395 --> 27:11.060
Or care.

27:11.062 --> 27:12.929
But whether or not you're happy,

27:12.931 --> 27:14.998
do you have to spoil our dinner?

27:15.000 --> 27:18.668
My concern is for Rachel.
My unhappiness...

27:18.670 --> 27:20.637
Honey. Sugar.

27:20.639 --> 27:22.905
Stop calling me food.

27:23.207 --> 27:24.374
This is not a stable home.

27:24.376 --> 27:28.845
She's with a single parent who's
an unemployed recluse

27:28.847 --> 27:32.749
who does nothing but plan
Corinthian sand columns.

27:32.751 --> 27:34.784
You can talk to me
about a lot of things,

27:34.786 --> 27:36.352
but parenting isn't one of them.

27:36.354 --> 27:39.722
You don't know the first thing
about being a parent.

27:39.724 --> 27:42.191
Maybe it's time
that I found out.

27:42.193 --> 27:46.195
Maybe Rachel should come
and live with us full-time.

28:03.080 --> 28:04.681
Rachel.

28:07.885 --> 28:11.287
Do you want to live
with Esther and Paul?

28:15.125 --> 28:16.392
No.

28:21.699 --> 28:23.399
Well, there you go.

28:25.002 --> 28:26.703
End of issue.

28:28.739 --> 28:32.375
You're not the first person
to lose someone you love.

28:32.377 --> 28:34.711
This isn't original.

28:51.228 --> 28:53.062
I'm going for a walk.

29:04.842 --> 29:07.844
[♪♪♪]

30:15.245 --> 30:20.049
Well, they brought somebody.
A woman. Living.

30:20.851 --> 30:22.552
Dead jokes. Funny.

30:22.554 --> 30:24.487
They're all ganging up, Gilles,

30:24.489 --> 30:28.558
sayin' it's time for me to get
over you and let you go.

30:30.127 --> 30:32.528
You don't want me
to let you go, do you?

30:32.530 --> 30:36.199
You can't ask me
questions like that.

30:36.201 --> 30:37.433
Why not?

30:37.435 --> 30:39.368
'Cause you know my wants.

30:39.370 --> 30:42.405
Or what I say I want is really
what you want me to want

30:42.407 --> 30:44.373
'cause I'm here right now
only in your mind,

30:44.375 --> 30:47.910
unless I'm real, which would
mean I'm kind of a ghost,

30:47.912 --> 30:51.514
which I know
you don't want me to believe

30:51.516 --> 30:54.016
'cause you hate
the idea of being crazy.

30:54.018 --> 30:56.085
Why do you always do that?
Do what?

30:56.087 --> 30:59.188
Fire back in rambling sentences
to confuse me.

30:59.190 --> 31:01.858
You do.
I don't do that.

31:01.860 --> 31:03.860
No, what you do is,
you ask questions

31:03.862 --> 31:05.394
you don't really
want me to answer.

31:05.396 --> 31:08.497
Whether I want to or not is moot
because you always dodge.

31:08.499 --> 31:09.966
You did it alive,
you do it dead.

31:09.968 --> 31:14.370
Are you seriously gonna try
to outtalk me?

31:28.952 --> 31:30.453
How's Rachel?

31:33.457 --> 31:35.124
She's good, I think.

31:35.126 --> 31:38.961
She seemed to have a good summer
with Paul and Esther.

31:40.631 --> 31:43.633
The one rule we had
was she comes first.

31:43.635 --> 31:45.968
We even stuck to that one.

31:47.638 --> 31:48.638
I know.

31:48.640 --> 31:50.072
She needs you to be there.

31:50.074 --> 31:52.108
Especially this weekend.

31:53.043 --> 31:54.510
I know that too.

32:00.584 --> 32:02.551
You're okay, Mr. Man.

32:08.392 --> 32:10.059
I miss you.

32:12.095 --> 32:13.663
You're okay.

32:17.601 --> 32:19.201
I gotta run.

32:19.569 --> 32:21.037
Get back here!

32:21.039 --> 32:23.339
Go play with the live girl!

32:23.341 --> 32:24.640
Gillian!

32:26.977 --> 32:28.511
Come on!

32:37.054 --> 32:39.021
Hey, kiddo.

32:39.156 --> 32:44.527
I heard you yelling.
Were you yelling at someone?

32:44.529 --> 32:45.661
Oh...

32:45.663 --> 32:49.098
Just myself.

32:50.400 --> 32:53.302
You talk to her, don't you?

32:53.304 --> 32:54.537
What?

32:54.539 --> 32:56.539
Mommy.
You talk to her out here.

32:56.541 --> 33:01.377
Oh, well, I talk to her all the
time, in my prayers.

33:04.181 --> 33:09.051
You talk to her like she's right
in front of you out here.

33:09.586 --> 33:11.520
No, that's...

33:11.522 --> 33:16.659
Well, sometimes
I fantasize about stuff.

33:19.229 --> 33:21.564
What's with this book
that you're writing?

33:21.566 --> 33:25.568
Well, you know, it's, uh...
you know, it's...

33:27.337 --> 33:30.106
You know.

33:30.108 --> 33:31.407
A lie?

33:31.409 --> 33:33.409
Well, yeah.

33:36.079 --> 33:38.080
Is everything okay?

33:39.449 --> 33:43.619
We haven't really talked much
since you've been back.

33:43.621 --> 33:47.623
Yeah, it was kind of hectic
those three days,

33:47.625 --> 33:50.059
what with just the two of us.

34:01.204 --> 34:03.764
Do I tell you I love you enough?

34:04.541 --> 34:06.275
You know, I read these studies.

34:06.277 --> 34:09.645
With teenagers, you're not
supposed to say it too much.

34:09.647 --> 34:11.213
They won't hear
it after a while.

34:11.215 --> 34:14.516
If you say it too little,
that can cause harm too.

34:14.518 --> 34:17.686
Do I say it too much?
Too little? I...

34:18.422 --> 34:20.589
I don't know.

34:24.460 --> 34:26.762
You say it the right amount.

34:36.606 --> 34:39.574
<b>♪ ["BILLY, DON'T BE A HERO" BY BO ♪
♪ DONALDSON & THE HEYWOODS PLAYS] ♪</b>

34:39.577 --> 34:43.679
<i>♪ Come back and</i>
<i>make me your wife ♪</i>

34:44.380 --> 34:47.315
<i>♪ And as he started to go ♪</i>

34:47.318 --> 34:52.321
<i>♪ She said,</i>
<i>Billy, keep your head low ♪</i>

34:52.322 --> 34:55.257
<i>♪ Billy, don't be a hero ♪</i>

34:55.259 --> 34:57.793
<i>♪ Come back to me ♪</i>

34:57.795 --> 34:59.662
CINDY:
Paul, take it outside.

34:59.664 --> 35:01.530
As far away as possible, okay?

35:01.532 --> 35:03.165
Okay, okay, I'm finished.

35:03.167 --> 35:03.732
Hi.
Hi, baby.

35:03.734 --> 35:07.269
PAUL:
Next time you're gonna
have to pay for this.

35:07.271 --> 35:08.571
You out talking to him?

35:08.573 --> 35:10.372
Yeah.

35:11.408 --> 35:12.441
How is he?

35:12.443 --> 35:15.678
He's fine.
He cooled off a little bit.

35:15.680 --> 35:17.213
He's fine now.

35:17.215 --> 35:18.848
What'd you talk about?

35:18.850 --> 35:21.217
Esther, he's fine, okay?

35:21.219 --> 35:22.885
Maybe you do butt
in a little too much.

35:22.887 --> 35:26.755
Well, I'm sorry, but sometimes
I get scared for him,

35:26.757 --> 35:29.391
and I get scared for you too.

35:30.193 --> 35:33.496
You can always tell me
to butt out, you know.

35:34.197 --> 35:35.531
Yeah.

35:38.168 --> 35:40.336
Just don't worry, okay?

35:40.537 --> 35:42.571
You don't have to worry.

35:46.343 --> 35:47.343
What?

35:47.345 --> 35:50.379
You tell me not to worry, but...

35:50.714 --> 35:53.149
am I wrong to worry?

35:58.321 --> 36:02.491
I'm tired.
I'm gonna go to bed.

36:03.460 --> 36:04.793
Good night.

36:07.197 --> 36:08.597
Good night.

36:46.503 --> 36:48.404
PAUL:
Why can't you sleep?

36:48.605 --> 36:51.307
ESTHER:
How did you know
I wasn't sleeping?

36:51.309 --> 36:55.578
When two people are together
long enough, they sense things.

36:55.946 --> 36:58.647
Plus which,
you snore like an elk.

37:00.750 --> 37:04.386
I have a court appointment
Monday morning.

37:06.256 --> 37:09.491
What do you mean
you have a court appointment?

37:13.496 --> 37:16.899
Rachel shouldn't be
living in this situation.

37:22.005 --> 37:23.572
You're going to a court of law?

37:23.574 --> 37:27.376
No, it's a tennis court.
I'm gonna play doubles.

37:27.378 --> 37:28.344
What are you thinking?

37:28.346 --> 37:30.779
She went from an A student
to C's and D's.

37:30.781 --> 37:32.314
No.
Her mother died!

37:32.316 --> 37:34.650
She still had
A's the year after.

37:34.652 --> 37:37.486
It was the second year
she started to bottom out.

37:37.488 --> 37:40.422
It's not Gillian. It's him.

37:40.424 --> 37:43.325
Her guidance counselor, whom
David doesn't even talk to,

37:43.327 --> 37:46.395
by the way, says that she's
retreating more and more.

37:46.397 --> 37:49.865
She's been laughing and having
fun the last two months.

37:49.867 --> 37:51.500
With us, but look at her here.

37:51.502 --> 37:52.735
She doesn't want to leave him.

37:52.737 --> 37:56.639
Of course not. Of course she
doesn't want to hurt her father.

37:56.641 --> 37:59.708
But she's the one
who's getting hurt.

37:59.710 --> 38:01.810
He's done nothing
to cause any judge

38:01.812 --> 38:03.479
anywhere to take
away his daughter.

38:03.481 --> 38:05.714
It's not your business.
So we're supposed to wait?

38:05.716 --> 38:08.017
He's her father.
She's my sister's daughter.

38:08.019 --> 38:09.652
You're not her mother,
you're an aunt,

38:09.654 --> 38:14.323
an aunt who might want to be
more, but still just an aunt.

38:14.325 --> 38:16.592
You want to write that down?
Fine.

38:16.594 --> 38:19.395
Maybe that way
you'll remember it.

38:21.998 --> 38:24.500
PAUL:
Don't do this, Esther.

38:26.036 --> 38:28.404
Don't do this.

38:30.707 --> 38:32.908
I don't want to do it.

38:38.348 --> 38:39.915
Let's just...

38:41.551 --> 38:44.620
Let's just see how
the weekend goes.

38:49.025 --> 38:50.893
<b>♪ ["FAITHFUL" BY CLETO ESCOBEDO ♪
♪ PLAYS OVER PA] ♪</b>

38:50.895 --> 38:53.762
<i>♪ I don't give my heart away</i>
